Brain Behavior and Immunity 119 (2024) 607–620
608
typhimurium (S. typhimurium) (Zeng et al., 2017). Salmonella induces 
acute enterocolitis and elicits cellular synthesis of pro-inflammatory 
cytokines, including TNF-α and IL-1β (Gal´an, 2021). Salmonella can 
also compromise the integrity of the gastrointestinal mucosal barrier, 
thereby exacerbating the inflammatory response in the surrounding 
tissues (Patel and McCormick, 2014). 
Moreover, study has documented the involvement of Salmonella in 
eliciting anxiety, depression, and cognitive deficits (Wu et al., 2022), 
which could be partly explained by lipopolysaccharide (LPS) leakage 
during infection (Li et al., 2023; Ushio et al., 2022). Some studies have 
reported that the vagus nerve is involved in gastrointestinal infection- 
induced anxiety-like behavioral changes (Agustí et al., 2018). The 
vagus nerve serves as the channel for direct communication between the 
gut microbiota and the CNS. The vagus nerve can detect products from 
gut and gut microbiota, such as LPS, histamine, TNF-α and IL-1β, and 
transmit these signals to the host’s nucleus of the solitary tract (NTS) 
(Hu et al., 2022; Mitra et al., 2023; Yu et al., 2020). A recent study 
indicated that vagus nerve cutting, i.e. vagotomy, effectively alleviated 
the anxiety-like behavior induced by gut microbiota from depressive 
mice (Siopi et al., 2023). Although studies have demonstrated that 
Salmonella activates the NTS through the vagus nerve (Wang et al., 
2002), the involvement of the vagus nerve in Salmonella-induced gut 
inflammation and anxiety-like behavior remains unclear. 
Salmonella disrupts indigenous gut microbiota homeostasis to 
establish colonization (Ahmer and Gunn, 2011), which can results in 
dysregulation of microbiota metabolites and affect the host’s physio­
logical state. (Yang and Cong, 2021). Gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA) 
serves as both a neurotransmitter and a microbial metabolites that can 
regulate gastrointestinal homeostasis (Sokovic Bajic et al., 2019). 
Although some studies have reported the anti-inflammatory and anti- 
infective effects of orally administered GABA-producing probiotics and 
intraperitoneal GABA administration (Liu et al., 2022; Tette et al., 
2022), there is a lack of research confirming the efficacy of oral GABA in 
resistance to Salmonella infection. 
Therefore, this study aimed to investigate the impact of the vagus 
nerve on anxiety-like behavior induced by Salmonella and to determine 
whether vagotomy during Salmonella infection can ameliorate gut 
inflammation by affecting the microbiota and its metabolites. We 
employed behavioral tests, immunofluorescence and PCR to explore the 
relationship 
between 
Salmonella 
infection-induced 
anxiety-like 
behavior and neural activation. Additionally, we utilized 16S rRNA 
amplicon sequencing and metabolomics to reveal changes in the gut 
microbiota composition and microbial metabolites. Overall, these find­
ings suggest that vagotomy prevents infection by promoting GABA 
synthesis in the colon and alleviating anxiety-like behavior. This study 
posits that targeting the vagus nerve may offer a novel and efficacious 
approach to preventing gastrointestinal infections and associated 
behavioral abnormalities. 
2. Materials and methods 
2.1. Animal experiment design 
All animal experiments were conducted using adult (8–10 weeks old) 
male C57BL/6J mice purchased from Charles River (Beijing, China) and 
began after the mice had accustomed the laboratory environment for 1 
week. All animals were housed in groups of four under controlled 
environmental conditions and were fed food and water ad libitum. The 
housing conditions were maintained at a constant temperature of 22 ±
2 ◦C with a 12 h/12 h light/dark cycle. The animal test protocol follows 
the guidelines for the care and use of laboratory animals (eighth edition, 
ISBN-10: 0-309-15, 396-4), and was approved by the Animal Ethics 
Committee of Northwest A&F University (Ethics No.XN2023-0516). 
Experiment 1: The mice were randomly divided into four groups (n 
= 10–12). (1) Sham group: Mice underwent sham surgery as the control 
(2) Sham + Salmonella group: mice underwent sham surgery followed by 
S. Typhimurium infection as the model. (3) Vagotomy group: Mice un­
derwent unilateral cervical vagotomy as the negative control. (4) Va­
gotomy + Salmonella group: Mice underwent unilateral cervical 
vagotomy followed by S. typhimurium infection. All animals were 
allowed a recovery period of 2 weeks post-surgery to ensure stabilization 
and healing. After that, mice in the Sham + Salmonella group and Va­
gotomy + Salmonella group underwent subsequent Salmonella infection 
modeling. Three days after infection, behavioral experiments were 
conducted. On the fifth day post-infection, mice were sacrificed, and 
serum, brain, spleen, fecal, intestine and gut samples were collected. 
Throughout the infection period, changes in mice’ body weight were 
recorded daily. 
Experiment 2: The mice were randomly divided into two groups (n =
10–12). (1) Salmonella group: Mice were infected with S. typhimurium. 
(2) Salmonella + GABA group: Mice were pre-treated with GABA (100 
mg/kg, i.g.) for 2 weeks (Once a day) prior to S. typhimurium infection. 
During Salmonella infection, mice were administered GABA daily. The 
subsequent experiments were conducted following the same protocol as 
Experiment 1. 
Experiment 3: The mice were randomly divided into five groups (n =
6–8). (1) Sham + Salmonella group: mice underwent a sham surgery 
followed by S. Typhimurium infection. (2) Vagotomy + Salmonella 
group: mice underwent unilateral cervical vagotomy followed by S. 
typhimurium infection. (3) VSG group: Mice underwent unilateral cer­
vical vagotomy followed by S. typhimurium infection. The mice 
received GABA intervention every day (100 mg/kg, i.g.) starting three 
days before Salmonella infection, until they were sacrificed. (4) VSPi.g. 
group: Mice underwent unilateral cervical vagotomy followed by S. 
typhimurium infection. Throughout the course of Salmonella infection, 
mice received daily treatment with picrotoxin (0.8 mg/kg, i.g.). (5) VSPi. 
p. group: The experimental procedure was the same as VSPi.g. group, 
with the only difference was changed to intraperitoneal injection of 
picrotoxin (0.8 mg/kg, i.p.). The subsequent experiments were con­
ducted following the same protocol as Experiment 1. 
2.2. Unilateral cervical vagotomy 
To avoid potential high mortality associated with bilateral cervical 
vagotomy, a unilateral cervical vagotomy was performed. Mice were 
anesthetized with isoflurane to create a 1.5 cm midline cervical incision, 
after which the right vagus nerve was isolated from the carotid artery 
and its associated connective tissue bundle. In mice undergoing vagot­
omy, the nerve was ligated using 6–0 silk sutures and excised at least 1 
cm. In sham-operated mice, the vagus nerve was gently isolated but not 
cut. Subsequently, mice were placed in isolated cages with a heating pad 
underneath to aid in recovery from anesthesia. After surgery, mice 
received intraperitoneal injections of antibiotics to prevent wound 
infection. Daily inspections were conducted to monitor the recovery of 
the incision sites and body weight. All mice were allowed a two-week 
rest period before being utilized in subsequent experiments. 
2.3. Bacterial strain culture 
All experiments were conducted using S. typhimurium strain 
SL1344. The bacterial strains were routinely cultured in Luria-Bertani 
(LB) broth for 14 h at 37 ◦C. After centrifugation at 500 x g for 10 
min, the bacterial suspension was diluted in PBS and used for subsequent 
gavage in mice. The OD600 value was used to determine the bacterial 
suspension concentration. 
2.4. Animal infections 
As described, mice were subjected to a 4-hour fasting period, during 
which water and food were withheld, preceding the administration of 
20 mg of streptomycin via gavage (Mu et al., 2019). Subsequently, mice 
were provided with ad libitum access to water and food. At 20 h after 
Q. Zou et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
Brain Behavior and Immunity 119 (2024) 607–620
609
streptomycin treatment, water and food were withdrawn again for 4 h 
before the mice were infected via oral gavage with 1 x 109 colony- 
forming units (CFU) of S. typhimurium in 100 μL of phosphate- 
buffered saline (PBS). Following the infection, mice were promptly 
offered ad libitum access to drinking water and food. 
2.5. Assessment of anxiety-like behavior by behavioral tests 
Open field: 
Animals were put in the center of white Plexiglas containers (50 ×
50 cm), and their behavior was recorded by a video camera for 5 min. 
The VisuTrack system (Xinruan, Shanghai, China) was used to map the 
center and peripheral zones and record the time spent in each zone. The 
testing area was cleaned with 70 % alcohol between two tests to prevent 
the influence of odors from mice. 
Marble Burying Test: 
The inside of the test cages in the Marble Burying Test was covered 
with a 5 cm deep wood chip cushion, and 20 glass marbles with a 
diameter of 15 mm were arranged in a 4 × 5 design on the wood chips. 
The mice were placed in a test cage, and the number of marbles buried 
within 30 min was recorded. A marble was considered buried when at 
least 2/3 of it was covered with wood chips. 
2.6. S. typhimurium burden in spleen 
The spleens of mice were collected in 1 ml of sterile PBS and ho­
mogenized by a KZ-III-F tissue grinding machine (Servicebio, Wuhan 
China). The tissue homogenate was then serially diluted and plated onto 
Xylose Lysine Deoxycholate Agar to enumerate the colony-forming units 
(CFU) of S. typhimurium in the spleen. In mouse experiments, values 
were set to the minimal detectable value (0 CFU for the spleen) for 
samples harboring no bacteria. 
2.7. LPS detection by ELISA analysis 
LPS content in the serum was quantified by an ELISA kit (Xinle 
Biotechnology, Shanghai, China). After centrifuging the blood sample at 
3000 rpm/min for 15 min, the serum was separated for the determina­
tion of LPS content, with all steps meticulously carried out as per the 
manufacturer’s instructions. 
2.8. Organ histological changes of the colon by hematoxylin and eosin 
(H&E) staining 
After the mice were sacrificed, the colon tissue was immersed in a 4 
% paraformaldehyde solution for fixation, rinsed with PBS and then 
dehydrated with a gradient of 75 %, 80 %, 95 %, and 100 % ethanol. 
Then, the tissue was embedded in paraffin to prepare 4 μm paraffin 
sections after all ethanol was removed. Tissue sections were deparaffi­
nized, rehydrated and stained with H&E. The sections were observed 
with an optical microscope after the staining process was completed. 
2.9. Quantification of goblet cell by alcian blue staining 
Colon tissue of mice was collected and fixed in a methanol-Carnot 
solution (60 % methanol, 30 % chloroform, 10 % glacial acetic acid) 
for 24 h. The tissue was then embedded vertically in paraffin and cut 
into 4 μm sections. Then the sections were deparaffinized, rehydrated 
and stained with Alcian Blue/Nuclear-Fast-Red. After section staining, 
the colon tissue sections were observed at magnification. The Image J 
software (National Institutes of Health, Bethesda, MD, USA) was used for 
further quantitative analysis of goblet cells. 
2.10. Detection of microglia and neuron activation by 
immunofluorescence staining 
After being anesthetized with avertin, the mice (n = 5 per group) 
were immediately perfused with cold normal saline and 4 % para­
formaldehyde. Brains were immediately removed and fixed in cold 4 % 
paraformaldehyde for 24 h. The tissues were immersed in gradient su­
crose solution to dehydrate and then serially cut into 10-μm-thick cor­
onal sections on a freezing microtome (Leica CM1850, Leica Instrument 
GmbH, Germany), and stored at −
80 ◦C until use. 
Immunofluorescence staining was performed according to the pre­
viously described methods. After cleaning the sections with PBS, non- 
specific staining was blocked by 0.25 % Triton and 10 % goat serum 
albumin. Sections were incubated overnight with the following primary 
antibodies at 4 ◦C: rabbit anti-cFos (1:500, Abcam, Cat No. ab18723), 
rabbit anti-IBA-1 (1:1000, Abcam, Cat No. ab 214672). Sections were 
incubated with Alexa Fluor (594)-conjugated anti-rabbit secondary 
antibodies at room temperature for 1 h. The sections were then washed 
six times, and then mounted with Mounting Medium (with DAPI). 
Immunofluorescence images were acquired using a confocal laser- 
scanning microscope (Andor, Belfast, Britain). Positive cells were 
calculated using the ImageJ software. 
2.11. Detection of mRNA by real-time polymerase chain reaction (RT- 
PCR) 
The total RNA was extracted from tissues using SteadyPure Universal 
RNA Extraction Kit (Accurate Biotechnology, Hunan, China), strictly 
following the manufacturer’s instructions. The cDNA samples were 
synthesized using the HiFiScript cDNA synthesis kit by RNA reverse 
transcription. The primers used in RT-qPCR are listed in Table 1. The 
level of RNA expressions was quantified using the SYBR Green Pro Taq 
HS qPCR Kit (Accurate Biotechnology, Hunan, China) and CFX96™ real- 
time system (Bio-Rad, Hercules, CA, USA). The results of RNA expres­
sion were calculated using the 2 −
ΔΔCt method. Conditions for real- 
time PCR were: initial denaturation for 30 s at 95 ◦C, followed by 
amplification cycles of 5 s at 95 ◦C, and 30 s at 60 ◦C. 
2.12. Neurotransmitter detection by LC-MS/MS analysis 
LC-MS/MS analysis was conducted using an Agilent 6410 triple stage 
quadrupole mass spectrometer equipped with an ESI ion source and an 
Agilent 1290 HPLC system with an auto-sampler (Agilent Technologies, 
Santa Clara, CA, USA). Briefly, the analytes were separated on a BEH 
C18 column (2.1 mm × 100 mm, 1.7 μm, Waters, Milford, USA) at 30 ◦C. 
The mobile phase, consisting of 0.1 % formic acid in water (Solvent A) 
and acetonitrile (Solvent B), was used with a gradient elution of 0–4 
min, 2 % B; 6 min, 80 % B; 8–10 min, 90 % B at a flowrate of 0.1 ml/min. 
ESI-MS/MS conditions were set as follows: gas temperature 325 ◦C, gas 
flow 10 min, capillary 4000 V, nebulizer pressure 35 psi. The detection 
of neurotransmitters such as Histamine, GABA, serotonin, and others 
using electrospray positive ionization in multiple reaction monitoring 
mode. 
