2.13. Bacterial identification by 16S rRNA sequencing 
Total community genomic DNA extraction was performed using a E. 
Z.N.A™ MagBind Soil DNA Kit (Omega,M5635-02,USA). The concen­
tration of the DNA was detected by using an Qubit 4.0 (Thermo, USA) to 
ensure that adequate amounts of high-quality genomic DNA had been 
extracted. 
PCR was started immediately after DNA was extracted. The 16S 
rRNA V3–V4 amplicon was amplified using 2 × Hieff® Robust PCR 
Master Mix (Yeasen, 10105ES03, China) and strictly following the 
manufacturer’s instructions. Two universal bacterial 16S rRNA gene 
PCR primers were used: the forward primer (CCTACGGGNGGCWGCAG) 
and the reverse primer (GACTACHVGGGTATCTAATCC). The plate was 
sealed and PCR performed on a thermal instrument (Applied Biosystems 
9700, USA). The PCR products were checked using electrophoresis in 2 
% (w/v) agarose gels in TBE buffer (Tris, boric acid, EDTA) stained with 
ethidium bromide (EB) and visualized under UV light. 
Sequencing was performed using the Illumina MiSeq system (Illu­
mina MiSeq, USA), according to the manufacturer’s instructions. After 
sequencing, the two short Illumina readings were assembled by PEAR 
software (version 0.9.8) and analyzed by standard methods. The effec­
tive tags were clustered into operational taxonomic units (OTUs) of ≥97 
% similarity using Usearch software (version 11.0.667). Chimeric se­
quences and singleton OTUs (with only one read) were removed, after 
which the remaining sequences were sorted into each sample based on 
the OTUs. The tag sequence with the highest abundance was selected as 
a representative sequence within each cluster. Bacterial and fungal OTU 
representative sequences were classified taxonomically by blasting 
against the RDP Database and UNITE fungal ITS Database, respectively. 
2.14. Statistical analysis 
All data were expressed as mean ± SEM. Statistical analyses were 
performed using the Prism software (GraphPad, version 9, San Diego, 
USA), with p < 0.05 considered statistically significant. Data were 
analyzed using unpaired t test for two group comparison tests or the one- 
way ANOVA followed by Tukey’s post-hoc test for multiple comparison 
tests. Data met the assumptions of the tests applied and variance was 
similar across the different groups in different experimental conditions. 
The α-diversity indices (including Chao, Simpson, and Shannon indices) 
were calculated with Mothur software (version 3.8.31). To estimate the 
diversity of the microbial community of the sample, two groups and 
multiple group comparisons were made using T test and ANOVA test 
respectively. Beta diversity was combined with dimensional reduction 
methods such as principal coordinate analysis (PCoA), non-metric 
multidimensional scaling (NMDS), or constrained principal component 
analysis (PCA) and were visualized using R vegan package (version 
2.5–6). Difference comparison was used to identify features with 
significantly different abundances between groups using STAMP 
(version 2.1.3) and LefSe (version 1.1.0). Correlation coefficients and p- 
values between communities/OTUs were calculated using SparCC 
(version 1.1.0), and correlation matrix heatmaps were drawn using R 
corrplot package (version 0.84). R ggraph package (version 2.0.0) is 
used to build network graphs. Further statistical tests were conducted in 
the Prism software. 
3. Results 
3.1. The mediating effects of vagotomy on S. typhimurium invasion- 
induced systemic infection and anxiety-like behavior 
This study elucidates the modulatory effects of vagotomy on Sal­
monella induced systemic infection and anxiogenic behaviors. Investi­
gation into the effects of Salmonella-induced systemic infection on 
anxiety-like behaviors and the interfacing role of the vagal nerve was 
conducted using a mice model subjected to vagotomy followed by 
Salmonella challenge. Behavioral and physiological responses were 
quantified (Fig. 1A). Notable systemic Salmonella infection, including 
pronounced weight loss, splenic edema, bacterial dissemination within 
the spleen, and augmented serum endotoxin levels, were all significantly 
attenuated following vagotomy (Fig. 1B-F). 
Assessment of anxiety-like behaviors employed the open field and 
marble-burying tests. The former indicated a marked reduction in lo­
comotor activity and central area entries post Salmonella infection in the 
Sham group, which was mitigated by vagotomy. Infected mice exhibit 
anxiety-related marble-burying behavior, which is ameliorated by va­
gotomy (Fig. 1 G-I). 
3.2. Vagotomy alleviated gut and brain inflammatory responses to 
S. typhimurium-induced infection 
S. typhimurium is known to incite gut inflammation (Kurtz et al., 
2017). Manifested by enhanced inflammatory cell infiltration, villous 
architecture compromise, and submucosal edema in the jejunum, which 
were alleviated by vagotomy (Fig. S1A). Similar pathological changes, 
including crypt loss, ulcerations, and lymphocytic infiltration in the 
colon, were also subdued post-vagotomy (Fig. 1J). Vagotomy reduced 
the loss of goblet cells, as indicated by Alcian blue staining (Fig. 1J & K). 
Furthermore, vagotomy significantly suppressed the infection- 
induced upregulation of pro-inflammatory cytokine mRNA, including 
TNF-α, IL-1β, IL-10, and IL-6 in the colon (Fig. 1L). Moreover, the 
expression of IL-22 and CXCL1, components of the host anti-infective 
response, was restored in vagotomized, infected mice (Fig. 1L, 
Fig. S1C & D), demonstrating the efficacy of vagotomy for dampening 
gut inflammatory cascades. 
Anxiogenic behavior is linked to neuroinflammation. Neuro­
inflammation was indicated by microglia activation and pro- 
inflammatory cytokines upregulation in the central nervous system. 
The intensification of microglial activation within the hippocampus post 
infection was evident through IBA-1 staining, a finding that was 
significantly subdued by vagotomy (Fig. 2A & C). Moreover, vagotomy 
significantly attenuated microglial hyperactivation within the amygdala 
(Fig. 2B & D). Correspondingly, the infection-driven surge in pro- 
inflammatory cytokines, such as IL-6, IL-1β, and TNF-α in the hippo­
campus, was mitigated by vagotomy (Fig. 2E-G), as was the elevation in 
IL-1β and IL-10 levels within the cortex (Fig. S2B). It confirmed that 
vagotomy effectively reduces microglial activation and neuro­
inflammation engendered by S. typhimurium infection. 
3.3. Vagotomy disrupts neural signal transmission in the gut-brain axis 
during S. typhimurium infection 
To investigate the potential activation of the brain via the vagus 
nerve, c-Fos protein expression served as a proxy for neuronal activity. 
Results demonstrated that Salmonella infection precipitated a marked 
upsurge in c-Fos positive cells within the nucleus tractus solitarius 
(NTS), which was significantly diminished by vagotomy (Fig. 3A & C, 
Fig. S3A). Analogous patterns of neuronal activation, diminished by 
vagotomy, were observed in the amygdala (Fig. 3B & D). The results 
suggested that Salmonella can stimulate neuronal activation in these 
regions, which was mitigated by vagotomy. 
3.4. The influence of neurotransmitter secretion in the colon induced by 
vagotomy during S. typhimurium infection 
Inquiry into neurotransmitter secretion alterations in the colon due 
to vagotomy during S. typhimurium infection revealed neurotransmit­
ters as pivotal in maintaining gut-brain axis equilibrium (Mittal et al., 
2017). LC-MS/MS analysis identified various neurotransmitters present 
within the colon, including N-acetyl serotonin, histamine, tryptophan, 
GABA, and glutamate (Fig. 4A). Salmonella infection notably suppressed 
levels of GABA, tryptophan, and N-acetyl serotonin, a suppression 
