reversed by vagotomy. Intriguingly, the vagotomy cohort exhibited 
significantly elevated levels of these neurotransmitters compared to the 
Sham group (Fig. 4B & E & F). Conversely, the concentrations of 
glutamate and histamine were significantly increased in the colons of 
Salmonella-infected mice and remained unaffected by vagotomy (Fig. 4C 
& D), indicating that Salmonella infection selectively modulates specific 
neurotransmitters in the colon, with certain alterations being reversible 
by vagotomy. 
3.5. Vagotomy alleviates the gut microbiota disruption induced by 
S. typhimurium infection 
Additionally, the research addressed how vagotomy modulates gut 
microbiota perturbations triggered by Salmonella infection. The gut 
microbiota is integral to colonic inflammatory regulation and neuro­
transmitter modulation within the gastrointestinal tract (Hou et al., 
2022). Alpha diversity analysis showcased a significant reduction in gut 
microbiota diversity following Salmonella infection, a decline not 
observed in vagotomized mice (Fig. 5A, Fig. S4A). Further, analysis of 
similarities (ANOSIM) underscored the pronounced differences between 
groups over within-group variations (Fig. S4C). 
Both principal coordinate analysis (PCoA) and principal component 
analysis (PCA) corroborated significant alterations in gut microbiota 
composition due to infection, which were distinct in the vagotomy- 
treated group (Fig. 5B, Fig. S4B). Notably, the predominant bacterial 
genera differed between groups, with an increase in Clostridium sensu 
stricto, Salmonella, and Ligilactobacillus in the Sham + Salmonella group 
(Fig. 5C). DESeq2 analysis revealed that vagotomy substantially 
modulated the microbiota profile, decreasing the abundance of patho­
genic bacteria like Salmonella and increasing the abundance of GABA- 
producing Alistipes, Bacteroides, and Lactobacillus (Fig. 5D). Vagotomy 
alone altered the abundance of several genera, enhancing those associ­
ated with beneficial gut functions (Fig. S4D). Additionally, according to 
Pearson correlation analysis, the presence of Salmonella in the colon 
exhibited a strong positive correlation with spleen index (r = 0.81, p <
0.01), and a robust negative correlation with the mice’s body weight (r 
= -0.91, p < 0.01) and exploratory behaviors such as center zone dis­
tance (r = -0.84, p < 0.01). An inverse relationship was also observed 
with colonic GABA levels (r = -0.84, p < 0.01) and the abundance of the 
beneficial bacterium Alitipes (r = -0.68, p < 0.01). (Fig. 5E). Collectively, 
these findings indicate that vagotomy can mitigate disruptions in gut 
microbiota induced by Salmonella infection, potentially restoring ho­
meostasis and contributing to disease amelioration. 
3.6. The mediating effects of GABA intervention alleviated on 
S. typhimurium invasion-infection induced systemic infection and anxiety- 
like behavior via gut-brain axis 
The beneficial potential of GABA in mitigating the effects of S. 
typhimurium infection on systemic infection and anxiety was investi­
gated (Fig. 6A). Pre-treatment with GABA resulted in increased body 
weight (Fig. 6B) and diminished systemic inflammatory markers such as 
