Q. Zou et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
Brain Behavior and Immunity 119 (2024) 607–620
613
serum endotoxin levels and spleen index in infected mice (Fig. 6C-E). 
Additionally, GABA pre-treatment significantly reduced anxiety-like 
behaviors as evidenced by changes in locomotor activity in the open 
field test and the marble-burying test (Fig. 6F-H), demonstrating its 
beneficial effects in alleviating anxiety induced by infection. 
Moreover, GABA intervention had a pronounced effect on gut and 
brain inflammation. Histological analysis indicated that GABA reduced 
inflammatory cell infiltration and maintained intestinal villi structure in 
the jejunum, and mitigated colonic histopathological changes such as 
crypt dropout and lymphocytic infiltration in infected mice (Fig. 6J). 
There was also a notable preservation of goblet cells, which are crucial 
for maintaining intestinal barrier function (Fig. 6J & K). GABA admin­
istration also resulted in a downregulation of pro-inflammatory cyto­
kines in the colon and an upregulation of cytokines involved in anti- 
infectious responses (Fig. 6I). In the hippocampus, GABA similarly 
decreased the expression of pro-inflammatory cytokines (Fig. 6L-N), 
signifying a broader anti-inflammatory effect. 
To investigate whether vagotomy attenuates Salmonella-induced gut 
inflammation and anxiety-like behavior is via enhancing GABA pro­
duction or not, GABA or GABA receptor inhibitor (picrotoxin) was 
administered to mice which had undergone vagotomy during Salmonella 
infection (Fig. 7A). The result indicated that supplementation with or 
without GABA, vagotomy could significantly alleviated Salmonella- 
induced weight loss, spleen edema, bacterial infection within the spleen, 
and serum LPS levels. Notably, all of these recoveries in vagotomized 
mice were markedly diminished by treatment with picrotoxin, a GABA 
receptor inhibitor, either by i.g. or i.p. intervention (Fig. 7B-F). 
Furthermore, during Salmonella infection, vagotomy combined with 
GABA intervention did not show superior alleviation of anxiety-like 
behavior than mice treated with vagotomy alone. Importantly, the 
GABA receptor inhibitor did not significantly abolish the alleviating 
effects of vagotomy on Salmonella-induced anxiety-like behavior 
(Fig. 7G-I). 
4. Discussion 
Our study revealed that vagotomy effectively reduced anxiety-like 
behavior, Salmonella invasion, and neural activation in the NTS and 
amygdala induced by Salmonella. Furthermore, activation of microglial 
cells and expression of inflammatory factors were observed in the hip­
pocampus and amygdala of Salmonella-infected mice. Moreover, we 
observed that the reduction of GABA and GABA-producing gut micro­
biota in the colon, induced by Salmonella infection, was reversed in 
vagotomized mice. Subsequent GABA or GABA receptor inhibitor sup­
plementation experiments validated the role of GABA in alleviating the 
systemic invasion of Salmonella and gastrointestinal inflammation. 
The mutual interactions between the gastrointestinal tract and the 
CNS were confirmed. A clinical investigation revealed a high incidence 
of anxiety and depression among individuals with IBD (Mikocka-Walus 
et al., 2016). In our past research, DSS-induced colitis mice exhibited 
anxiety and depression-like behavior, accompanied by increased in­
flammatory cytokines and microglial activation (Zhang et al., 2020). 
Consistent with previous analyses (Goehler et al., 2008; Kaur et al., 
2020; Wu et al., 2022), we also found that pronounced anxiety-like 
behavior during acute Salmonella infection. Moreover, we observed 
that behavioral abnormalities induced by Salmonella could be restored in 
mice subjected to vagotomy (Fig. 1). 
The afferent fiber endings of the vagus nerve can rapidly sense 
immunological or endocrine signals originating, including LPS, IL-1β, 
TNF-α, glutamate and histamine, from the stomach, small intestine, and 
colon (Bonaz et al., 2017; Kaelberer et al., 2018). Numerous studies 
indicated that intraperitoneal LPS injection can activate the vagus nerve. 
Vagotomy ameliorates anxiety and depression-like behaviors induced by 
intraperitoneal LPS injection but cannot impact the effects caused by 
