615
intravenous and intramuscular LPS injection (Konsman et al., 2000; 
Romanovsky et al., 2000). Additionally, the scarcity of reports on the 
activation of the vagus nerve by intestinal LPS. In our study, we also 
observed an elevation in LPS levels in the serum during Salmonella 
infection (Fig. 1F). Based on these studies, we speculated that the in­
crease of LPS in serum may not be a primary contributor to Salmonella 
stimulating the vagus nerve but rather an indication of the severity of 
the Salmonella infection (Hosoi et al., 2005). 
The peripheral axon terminals of the vagus nerve express numerous 
receptors for cytokines, including IL-6, IL-1β, and TNF-α (Chavan et al., 
2017). When cytokines bind to their respective receptors, it triggers the 
activation of sensory signals within the vagus nerve (Pavlov and Tracey, 
2012; Yang et al., 2022). Recent research using nerve electrodes 
confirmed that when the vagus nerve is stimulated by IL-1β or TNF-α, 
cytokine-specific signals travel to the brain (Zanos et al., 2018). Thus, 
peripheral inflammatory factors could be sensed by the vagal afferents. 
As Salmonella can induce the release of pro-inflammatory factors from 
infected cells, we observed an overexpression of IL-1β and TNF-α in the 
colon (Xiao et al., 2023). Therefore, we hypothesized that Salmonella 
may activate the vagus nerve through inflammatory factors. Some 
studies reported that pathogenic bacteria directly infect human intesti­
nal endocrine cells and up-regulate glutamate synthesis (Dlugosz et al., 
2014). A recent study revealed that a type of intestinal endocrine cell 
can establish a direct synaptic connection with the vagus afferent nerve 
and activate the vagus nerve through glutamate (Kaelberer et al., 2018). 
We also observed a significant increase in the level of glutamate in the 
infected colon (Fig. 4). Thus, we support the hypothesis that pathogens 
manipulate the CNS and influence behavior through influencing gluta­
mate secretion from intestinal cells during infections (Sgritta et al., 
2019). Furthermore, previous research indicated that histamine in the 
gastrointestinal tract activates the vomiting reflex through the vagus 
nerve (Ono et al., 2019).We also found that the level of histamine in the 
colon was increased during Salmonella infection (Fig. 4). It was possible 
that histamine was one of the indirect mechanisms by which Salmonella 
stimulated the vagus nerve. Due to the complex environment of the 
gastrointestinal tract and the diversity of receptors on the vagus nerve 
