617
surface, the precise mechanism by which Salmonella activates the vagus 
nerve can be investigated through the co-culture of Salmonella with the 
intestinal vagus nerve in the future. 
Some research indicated that vagal afferent signaling implicates 
modulating memory and emotion, including innate anxiety and fear 
(Klarer et al., 2014; Suarez et al., 2018). The gut microbiota from 
depressive mice required the involvement of the vagus nerve to induce 
depressive-like behavior in normal mice (Siopi et al., 2023). The in­
vestigations observed neuroactivation in the PVN, NTS, and supraoptic 
nucleus during Salmonella infection (Riley et al., 2013; Wang et al., 
2002). Consistently, neural activation in the NTS was observed in Sal­
monella-infected mice. The attenuation of signal activation in vago­
tomized mice confirmed that Salmonella transmits signals to the CNS 
through the vagus nerve. In our study, it was noteworthy that abnormal 
neural activation was identified in the amygdala could be mitigated 
through vagotomy (Fig. 3). The amygdala is among the downstream 
regions projected by the NTS. Following vagus nerve activation, signals 
originating from the gastrointestinal tract traversed the NTS and were 
subsequently directed to the amygdala impacting emotions and behav­
ioral motivation (Han et al., 2018; Han et al., 2022). This indicates that 
anxiety-like behavior induced by Salmonella infection may be linked to 
the activation of emotion-related brain regions via the vagus nerve. 
The inflammatory response of the CNS plays a crucial role in eliciting 
anxiety-like behaviors. Alterations in inflammatory cytokines in specific 
brain regions, such as the amygdala and hippocampus, often influence 
individual behavior, cognition, and emotion (Guo et al., 2022; Troubat 
et al., 2021; Zheng et al., 2021). Numerous studies have demonstrated 
that stress-induced and neuroinflammatory animals typically exhibit 
heightened microglial activation and increased production of inflam­
matory factors in the amygdala and hippocampus, accompanied by 
anxiety-like behaviors (Cheng et al., 2019; Le´on-Rodríguez et al., 2022; 
Li et al., 2014; Zheng et al., 2021). Similar to prior investigations, our 
study revealed a substantial presence of activated microglia in the hip­
pocampus and amygdala of Salmonella-infected mice (Fig. 2). During 
Salmonella infection, vagotomy effectively alleviated the significant in­
crease in hippocampal expression of TNF-α, IL-6, and IL-1β. We 
considered that this phenomenon was linked to the abnormal activation 
of signals from the periphery to the CNS through the vagus nerve. 
Some studies showed that Salmonella can modify colonization resis­
tance in the intestine of mice, disrupt the homeostasis of the normal gut 
microbiota, and induce colitis (Ferreira et al., 2011; Zha et al., 2019). 
Our study demonstrated that Salmonella infection induced substantial 
disruption of the microbiota and gastrointestinal inflammation, with 
these effects being mitigated by vagotomy. Notably, Salmonella, Clos­
tridium sensu stricto, and Escherichia Shigella were significantly down- 
regulated in mice subjected to vagotomy (Fig. 5). The abundance of 
probiotic strains such as Lactobacillus, Alistipes, and Bacteroides exhibited 
up-regulation in mice undergoing vagotomy. Extensive research 
