Q. Zou et al.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     
Brain Behavior and Immunity 119 (2024) 607–620
618
demonstrated that anxiety can disrupt the balance of gut microbiota and 
potentially compromise intestinal permeability through various mech­
anisms (Madison and Kiecolt-Glaser, 2019). Hence, we hypothesized 
that inducing anxiety-like behavior in the host disrupted the intestinal 
microenvironment, serving as a colonization strategy for Salmonella. The 
induction of anxiety-like behavior during Salmonella infection repre­
sents one of the strategies employed to disrupt the native gut microbiota 
for the purpose of its own colonization. Additionally, we found subtle 
alteration of gut microbiota in mice subjected to vagotomy before 
infection, compared to sham mice. Although limited research existed on 
how vagotomy impacted the gut microbiota, a study involving vagot­
omy in the liver branch of mice also noted an alteration in the gut 
microbiota (Zhang et al., 2021). Moreover, research demonstrated that 
vagotomy led to a shift in the phenotype of peritoneal macrophages 
(Dalli et al., 2017). We speculate that this effect may result from 
diminished signals transmitted by the vagus efferent nerve to the 
gastrointestinal tract. Over time, this accumulation of altered signaling 
leads to partial alteration in the composition of the gut microbiota. In 
future studies, the role and mechanism of anxiety-like responses in 
Salmonella infection could be systematically investigated by developing 
an anxiety-like mouse model. Furthermore, it is crucial to screen and co- 
culture intestinal endocrine substances and intestinal immune cells post- 
vagotomy to explore their influence on the gut microbiota. 
Evidence suggested that Lactobacillus, Alistipes, and Bacteroides were 
probiotics believed to synthesize GABA (Strandwitz et al., 2019). 
Abundant studies have demonstrated that GABA can reduce the 
expression of IL-1β in inflammatory macrophages and intestinal 
epithelial cells, increase the expression of tight junction proteins, 
ameliorate villus and crypt damage, regulate the polarization of enteric 
glial cells, and exert anti-inflammatory effects on intestinal inflamma­
tion (Deng et al., 2023; Fu et al., 2022; Sokovic Bajic et al., 2019). The 
changes in the expression of IL-22 and CXCL1 may be attributed to the 
alteration of GABA in the gut induced by vagotomy. Some studies have 
indicated that GABA can systemically activate TH17 cell differentiation, 
promote macrophage polarization, and enhance resistance to infection 
(Kim et al., 2018; Ren et al., 2019). Therefore, GABA may increase the 
expression of IL-22 and CXCL1 in the gut through influencing Th17 cells 
and macrophages (Orecchioni et al., 2019). In this study, we observed 
that the decreased GABA level in gut was caused by Salmonella infection 
and was reversed in vagotomized mice (Fig. 4). Additionally, correlation 
analysis indicated a negative association between GABA level in gut and 
both blood LPS, spleen index and Salmonella relative abundance in colon 
(Fig. 5). This suggests that the level of GABA plays a crucial role in 
influencing colon symptoms. Hence, we speculate that GABA suppresses 
the abnormal inflammatory induced by Salmonella and promotes the 
recovery of gastrointestinal epithelial cells. 
Subsequent GABA treatment confirmed the anti-infective and anti- 
inflammatory effects of GABA (Fig. 6). Furthermore, supplementation 
with GABA or GABA receptor inhibitor in vagotomized mice indicated 
the alleviating effect of vagotomy on Salmonella infection is dependent 
on the production of GABA in the colon (Fig. 7). Importantly, the GABA 
or GABA receptor inhibitor did not affect the alleviating effects of va­
gotomy on Salmonella-induced anxiety-like behavior. These findings 
indicate that the preventive effect of vagotomy on Salmonella-induced 
anxiety-like behavior is independent of enhanced GABA levels in the 
colon. The improvement in anxiety-like behavior following vagotomy is 
attributed to its reduction of gut infection signals transmitted to the 
brain, which induce anxiety behavior. We found that gut microbiota 
influences stress responses through the vagus nerve, in agreement with 
previous studies (Siopi et al., 2023). Furthermore, the study also sug­
gests that alterations in gut microbiota can affect the signals transmitted 
from the gut to the brain via the vagus nerve (Rei et al., 2022). Thus, the 
possible mechanism of the preventive effects of GABA treatment on 
Salmonella-induced anxiety-like behavior could be the result of GABA 
inhibiting Salmonella colonization, thereby reducing neural signal 
transmission. However, the mechanisms by which the anti-infective and 
anti-inflammatory effects of GABA are affected need to be investigated. 
Future explorations will delve into whether GABA directly inhibits the 
expression of Salmonella virulence factors or indirectly hinders Salmo­
nella invasion by modifying the physiological state of gut cells. 
Certain limitations exist in our study. Although we observed alter­
ations in the gut microbiota after vagotomy, the precise mechanisms 
underlying this change remain ambiguous. We can only speculate that 
the impact of vagotomy on central-peripheral signaling, leading to al­
terations in the gut microenvironment. Secondly, the interaction be­
tween Salmonella and the vagus nerve needs further exploration. Future 
investigations may involve constructing Salmonella with a less immu­
nogenic LPS structure to avoid TLR receptor activation, allowing for 
further exploration of which substances from Salmonella can activate the 
vagus. Lastly, utilizing chemical genetic and neural tracing methods can 
help map the detailed neural circuits involved in Salmonella-induced 
anxiety. 
In summary, this study revealed that Salmonella can activate the 
host’s CNS via the vagus nerve, resulting in anxiety-like behavior and 
localized CNS inflammation. Simultaneously, vagus nerve blocking 
inhibited the disruption of gut microbiota and its metabolites induced by 
Salmonella infection and colonic damage. Furthermore, it elucidated the 
role of oral GABA intervention in conferring resistance to Salmonella 
infection. This study underscores the critical role of the vagus nerve in 
relaying signals of gut infection to the brain and posits that targeting the 
gut-brain axis may offer a novel and efficacious approach to preventing 
gastrointestinal infections and associated behavioral abnormalities. 
